passages.text: Following Carlsmed's 2Q25 earnings results, we summarize our key takeaways from the quarter and forward outlook. We note that our previous model and consensus figures included preliminary 2Q results, so we focus our commentary on the forward outlook.

Results and guidance in context: Revenue of \(\) 12.1\(million increased 99\% YoY and compared to GSe and consensus (FactSet Data, unless otherwise noted) of\) \ \(12.0\) million. Down the P&L, gross margins of \(73.4\%\) reflect 160 bps of compression on a YoY basis driven by elevated manufacturing costs as the company incurs expedited production fees to deliver implants within 10 days. Gross margin performance came in ahead of GSe of \(72.8\%\) , driving lower adjusted EBITDA / loss than contemplated in our estimates ( \(\) 6.2\(million reported vs. GSe of\) \ \(6.5\) million). The company continues to invest heavily in OpEx for growth in the quarter at \(127\%\) of revenue with particular emphasis on hiring sales representatives, AI investments in R&D, and costs related to standing up a public company. For 2025, the company introduced revenue guidance of \(\) 45.5-\ \(475\) million vs. pre- 2Q consensus of \(\) 45.7\(million (e.g. mid - point of full year outlook exceeding Street expectations by\) \sim 2\% \(). With the company's first quarter as a public company complete and above - consensus guidance for 2025, we view 2Q as a strong start for Carlsmed.

Updates from the earnings call and management follow- up: Major themes included: (1) key drivers of procedure volume growth; (2) the assumptions baked into 2025 revenue guidance and the expected cadence of revenue throughout the remainder of the year; (3) qualitative commentary on surgeon education and training initiatives where the company is tracking ahead of internal plans; (4) a review of planned uses of IPO proceeds, largely to support commercial expansion and product development initiatives; and (5) progress updates on the launch of the cervical implant offering where the first in human procedure was completed in the quarter with commercialization still contemplated in 2026.

Changes to our model (full details in Exhibit 2): We revise our forecasts to reflect (1) Q2 results, 10Q filing, and inaugural 2025 guidance; (2) commentary surrounding surgeon education and training initiatives; and (3) updated P&L assumptions. In aggregate, we are making immaterial changes to our Street high revenue estimates, as we remain confident in Carlsmed's forward growth
outlook and potential for further upside.

Implications to stock thesis: Carlsmed's 2Q aligned with preliminary results that the company reported in its \(5 - 1\) on July 15th. The positive surprise on the full year outlook aligns with our forecasts and reflects higher than planned surgeon adds in 2Q and the flow through effect to forward revenue performance. In this context, we think it is important to consider the impact of key business drivers with both new surgeons and ramp of experienced surgeons serving as major inputs to the model. Given favorable reimbursement economics, we expect pricing to remain stable for 2025, although we do forecast industry standard LSD% declines starting in 2026, which given the differentiation of the Aprevo technology, could end up being a conservative assumption. As for new product launches, we continue to project cervical volumes contributing in 2026 with a more meaningful step- up in 2027+. From a financial and operational perspective, all metrics are tracking in- line with our view that the company's recent capital raise represents sufficient resources to turn adjusted EBITDA and cash flow positive without additional financing needs. Putting this all together, we maintain our Buy rating and \(\) 19\$ price target (39% upside potential) and view current valuation (4.3x GSe 2026E sales) as offering compelling risk/reward.

Our 12- month price target, which continues to be based on 5.7x applied to our Q5- Q8 (3Q26- 2Q27) sales estimates, is unchanged at \$19.

Slower than anticipated hiring, onboarding, or ramping of sales reps as the company transitions to targeting a wider user base could pressure our adoption estimates. Changes to the MS- DRG and NTAP codes that enable incremental reimbursement such that hospitals and patients are not incurring additional costs to use Aprevo. Competition intensifies with additional entrants to the customized implant space or greater than anticipated uptake of robotics (Stryker's MAKO in limited market release) could strengthen the competitive environment and pressure Aprevo uptake.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
